Summary: We propose to use TESS 2-minute light curves, combined with new and flexible stellar flare and starspot analysis methods, to search for transiting exoplanets around active M dwarfs that have previously evaded detection. Although M dwarfs are some of the most important targets for current exoplanet studies, their flare and starspot activity often result in light curves that are too noisy for exoplanet detection pipelines. Using careful flare detection and modeling, along with flexible starspot detrending methods, we will be able to carry out the most complete search for transiting exoplanets around active M dwarfs to date. This search will in turn place strong constraints on the planet occurrence rate and dynamical stability timescales for these important planet hosts.
